2024-02-26

Load the data

HSB <- read.csv("HSB_data.csv")

# to make public = 0
HSB$sector <- factor(HSB$sector, levels=c("Public", "Catholic"))

Run model 4 - Intercepts and Slopes as Outcomes

Running model 4 means specifying the cross level interactions. This is sort of tricky, but essentially, you want an interaction term between any level-1 predictor with random slope and any level-2 predictor that is “predicting” that random variation.

This is easier if we look at the Hierarchical version of the model again:

  • Level 1
    • \(Y_{ij} = \beta_{0j} + \beta_{1j}(cses_{ij}) + r_{ij}\)
  • Level 2
    • \(\beta_{0j} = \gamma_{00} + \gamma_{01}(mean.ses_{j}) + \gamma_{02}(Sector_{j}) + u_{0j}\)
    • \(\beta_{1j} = \gamma_{10} + \gamma_{11}(mean.ses_{j}) + \gamma_{12}(Sector_{j}) + u_{1j}\)

So we know we have 3 predictor variables: cses (at level 1) and mean.ses and sector at level 2 Why do we need to specify interactions again?

Because the combined model includes interactions. This is due to the fact that when we substitute the level 2 equation for \(\beta_{1j}\) into the level 1 equation, it means the entire level 2 equation is multiplied by \(cses_{ij}\) so we have:

\[ Y_{ij} = [\gamma_{00} + \gamma_{01}(mean.ses_{j}) + \gamma_{02}(Sector_{j}) + u_{0j}] + [cses \times (\gamma_{10} + \gamma_{11}(mean.ses_{j}) + \gamma_{12}(Sector_{j}) + u_{1j})] + r_{ij} \] In the first bracket above, we have the substitution of \(\beta_{0j}\) with the level-2 equation for it. Since \(\beta_{0j}\) is the intercept, and not multiplied by anything, these terms just add right in.

However, in the second set of brackets, we see that the equation for \(\beta_{1j}\) gets multiplied by the level-1 predictor \(cses_{ij}\) because that’s how it’s written at level 1. Multiplying through we have

\[ Y_{ij} = [\gamma_{00} + \gamma_{01}(mean.ses_{j}) + \gamma_{02}(Sector_{j}) + u_{0j}] + [(cses \times\gamma_{10}) + (cses \times \gamma_{11}(mean.ses_{j})) + (cses \times \gamma_{12}(Sector_{j}))+ (cses \times u_{1j})] + r_{ij} \]

Rearranging our terms we see that the first 4 fixed effects (including the intercept) are not interactions, the next 2 are, and then we have the random part. Note that in the random part there is an interaction between \(cses\) and \(u_{ij}\) but lmer specifies this for us.

\[ Y_{ij} = \gamma_{00} + \gamma_{01}(mean.ses_{j}) + \gamma_{02}(Sector_{j}) + \gamma_{10}(cses) + \gamma_{11}(mean.ses_{j} \times cses) + \gamma_{12}(Sector_{j} \times cses)+ u_{0j} + u_{1j}(cses) + r_{ij} \] So we insert the fixed effects into the lmer formula, and then specify random cses slopes as with model 3 (cses|school) and lmer takes care of the rest.

Note: You can use * or : for interaction terms, but the * is better here as it will build the necessary terms for you without duplication or omission. Using : you would need to specify each term in the equation. See below (mod4alt):

# using the * operator for interactions
mod4 <- lmer(mathach ~ cses*mean.ses + cses*sector + (cses | school), data = HSB)

# alternate specification forming interaction terms "by hand" with ":"
mod4alt <- lmer(mathach ~ cses + mean.ses + sector + cses:mean.ses + cses:sector + 
                  (cses|school), data = HSB)

In the output, we can see that, indeed, we have the correct interaction variables in the model. Now, what do they mean?

Mean SES and Student SES

The cses:mean.ses term in the model is positive, and has a t-value that is likely significant (3.477). This means that the student ses relation to math achievement gets more positive as the school’s average SES increases. So schools with a higher mean SES tend to have stronger student-level ses effects on math achievement. This is true because the marginal cses slope is positive, so the positive interaction term adds to the already positive slope.

Sector and Student SES

In contrast, the cses:sectorCatholic term in the model is negative, but with a large t-value, which is also likely significant. It tells us that on average, Catholic schools have slopes that are -1.6427 less than Public schools. So the effect of student-level ses on math achievement is weaker in Public Schools, but still net positive on average.

Graphing

To understand the interaction between mean.ses and cses, it’s helpful to split Mean SES into categories and plot the different schools. We do this using the cut command.

In cut we specify breaks = 3 to just let R pick 3 equally spaced categories that we name low, average, and high ses. There are better ways to do it, but this is a nice quick and dirty method

HSB$mean.ses.cat <- cut(HSB$mean.ses,
                        breaks = 3,
                        labels = c('lowSES','averageSES','highSES'))

As before, we will use the ggplot2 package to make the graphs. Consult Hadley Wickham’s e-Book Chapter 3 for an introduction to the syntax.

Here’s the example from the PowerPoint slides, but with the entire 160 school data set.

Note, I am colorblind so I’m using this (rather ugly) colorblind palette, which is just a collection of hex codes for colors that have good contrast.

cbbPalette <- c("#000000", "#E69F00", "#56B4E9", "#009E73", "#F0E442", "#0072B2", "#D55E00", "#CC79A7")

ggplot(data = HSB, aes(x = cses, y = mathach, col = mean.ses.cat, group = school)) +
  #geom_point(size = 1, alpha = .7, position = "jitter") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_color_manual(values = cbbPalette[1:3]) +
  geom_smooth(method = lm,
              se     = FALSE,
              size   = .4, 
              alpha  = .7) + # to add regression line
  labs(title    = "SES and Math Achievement",
       subtitle = "The within-school regression lines colored by MeanSES")

As can be seen, there is a clear difference in the slopes across the 3 categories of Mean SES. Note that in this way, we’re really seeing the multilevel part in action. We have 2 sample levels, one of the 7185 students, and now we can see that the 160 schools make up a second (random) sample. This random sample has systematic components, one of them being Mean SES. But instead of just looking at the relation between this level-2 systematic component and a measurement, we looking at the relationship between the level-2 systematic component and the strength of a level-1 relationship.

Plotting only a sample of schools

Sometimes it’s easier to plot only some of the schools. Here is code that takes a sample of schools and plots them. Note, every time you run the schools <- sample(HSB$school, 50) command it will select different schools, so the plot will look a bit different every time that happens.

schools <- sample(HSB$school, 50)

Sampledata <- HSB[is.element(HSB$school,schools), ]

ggplot(data = Sampledata, aes(x = cses, y = mathach, col = mean.ses.cat, group = school)) +
  #geom_point(size = 1, alpha = .7, position = "jitter") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_color_manual(values = cbbPalette[1:3]) +
  geom_smooth(method = lm,
              se     = FALSE,
              size   = .4, 
              alpha  = .7) + # to add regression line
  labs(title    = "SES and Math Achievement",
       subtitle = "The within-school regression lines colored by MeanSES")

Building a model with deviance tests

Although we’ve used the t-values above as proxies for significance tests, we can also test the variance terms. Here, we’re going back a step to see if we need to actually specify predictors at level-2.

Let’s now see how we can “test” the significance of the random intercepts and slopes (the variance terms). This follows p. 84 of Raudenbush and Bryk (2002).

Fit the models to compare

We already have our test model: Model 4 with intercepts and slopes as outcomes (implying that both intercepts and slopes are random)

That model has the following variance components with \(\tau_{10} = \tau_{01}\)

\[ \begin{bmatrix} \tau_{00} & \tau_{01} \\ \tau_{10} &\tau_{11} \end{bmatrix} \] We will test the null hypothesis:

\[ H_{0}: \tau_{10} = \tau_{01} = \tau_{11} = 0 \] That is accomplished by fitting a model with random intercepts only model:

  • Level 1
    • \(Y_{ij} = \beta_{0j} + \beta_{1j}(cses_{ij}) \beta_{2j}(cses_{ij} \times mean.ses{j})+ \beta_{3j}(cses_{ij} \times Sector{j}) + r_{ij}\)
  • Level 2
    • \(\beta_{0j} = \gamma_{00} + \gamma_{01}(mean.ses_{j}) + \gamma_{02}(Sector_{j}) + u_{0j}\)
    • \(\beta_{1j} = \gamma_{10}\)
    • \(\beta_{2j} = \gamma_{20}\)
    • \(\beta_{3j} = \gamma_{30}\)

Which would look like this as a combined model:

\[ Y_{ij} = \gamma_{00} + \gamma_{01}(mean.ses_{j}) + \gamma_{02}(Sector_{j}) + \gamma_{10}(cses) + \gamma_{20}(cses_{ij} \times mean.ses{j})+ \gamma_{30}(cses_{ij} \times Sector{j}) + r_{ij} \] In lme4 language we have:

mod4_test <- lmer(mathach ~ cses*mean.ses + cses*sector + (1 | school), data = HSB)

# model 4_test VCOV
VarCorr(mod4_test)
##  Groups   Name        Std.Dev.
##  school   (Intercept) 1.5412  
##  Residual             6.0635
# model 4 VCOV
VarCorr(mod4)
##  Groups   Name        Std.Dev. Corr 
##  school   (Intercept) 1.54259       
##           cses        0.31787  0.391
##  Residual             6.05980

Note that mod4_test indeed has 2 fewer unique variance components.

Now we must perform the likelihood ratio test, which is a test of the Deviance statistics from the models. For a model to fit better, the deviance must be smaller (it is like a residual).

Below is code using anova().

Note when testing variance components, we should specify refit = FALSE to retain the REML results of our models. See Snijders & Bosker for more.

anova(mod4, mod4_test, refit = F)
## Data: HSB
## Models:
## mod4_test: mathach ~ cses * mean.ses + cses * sector + (1 | school)
## mod4: mathach ~ cses * mean.ses + cses * sector + (cses | school)
##           npar   AIC   BIC logLik deviance  Chisq Df Pr(>Chisq)
## mod4_test    8 46521 46576 -23252    46505                     
## mod4        10 46524 46592 -23252    46504 1.1241  2       0.57

Here we see that actually, the null hypothesis is retained, the model without random slopes fits just as well as that with the random slopes.
